c and Ayuujk peoples paved their own paths to a transnational lifeway during the Trump era. This meant adapting digital technology to their needs, setting up their own infrastructure, and designing new digital formats for re-organizing community life in all its facets—including illness, death and mourning, collective celebrations, sport tournaments, and political meetings—across vast distances. Author Ingrid Kummels shows how mediamakers and users in the Sierra Norte villages and in Los Angeles created a transborder media space and aligned time regimes. By networking from multiple places, they put into practice a communal way of life called Comunalidad and an indigenized American Dream—in real time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunication and culturezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aCommunication and culturezMexicozSierra Norte (Oaxaca) 0aInternet and indigenous peopleszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aInternet and indigenous peopleszMexicozSierra Norte (Oaxaca) 0aMixe IndiansxUrban residencezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aMixe IndianszLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aMixe IndianszMexicozSierra Norte (Oaxaca)xSocial conditions. 0aTransnationalism. 0aZapotec IndiansxUrban residencezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aZapotec IndianszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aZapotec IndianszMexicozSierra Norte (Oaxaca)xSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acalifornia, mexican, latino, latina, latinx, Hispanic, immigration, migration, emigration, expat, undocumented, illegal immigration, Oaxaca, oaxacan, Zapotec, Ayuujk, indigenous, native, sierra norte, race, ethnicity, culture, racism, xenophobia, discrimination, anthropology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978